SELECT insert_batch_questions('[{"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In Young''s double slit experiment, two slits are separated by 0.5 mm and the screen is placed 1 m away. If the wavelength of light used is 500 nm, the fringe width is:", "explanation": "Using beta = lambdaD/d = (500 x 10^-9 x 1) / (0.5 x 10^-3) = (5 x 10^-7) / (5 x 10^-4) = 1 x 10^-3 m = 1 mm. The fringe width is 1 mm.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["fringe-width", "numerical-problem", "ydse-formula"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-05", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.5 mm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1 mm", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "2 mm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "0.1 mm", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Check your calculation. 0.5 mm results from an error such as using d = 1 mm instead of 0.5 mm.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error in substitution"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "2 mm would result from using d = 0.25 mm instead of 0.5 mm. Recheck the slit separation value.", "misconception": "Incorrect unit conversion or value substitution"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "0.1 mm is 10 times too small. Verify that all units are converted to SI before substituting into the formula.", "misconception": "Unit conversion error (using mm instead of m for wavelength)"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In Young''s experiment, if the intensity of light from each slit is I_0, the intensity at a point where the phase difference between the two waves is pi/2 is:", "explanation": "The resultant intensity in YDSE is given by I = 4*I_0*cos^2(phi/2). When phi = pi/2, we get I = 4*I_0*cos^2(pi/4) = 4*I_0*(1/sqrt(2))^2 = 4*I_0*(1/2) = 2*I_0.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["intensity-distribution", "phase-difference", "interference-pattern"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-06", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "4*I_0", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "I_0", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "2*I_0", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "0", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "4*I_0 is the maximum intensity at a bright fringe where phi = 0 (perfectly constructive interference), not where phi = pi/2.", "misconception": "Thinking any non-zero phase difference gives maximum intensity"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "I_0 would require cos^2(phi/2) = 1/4, which corresponds to phi = 2*pi/3, not pi/2.", "misconception": "Incorrectly evaluating the cosine function"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Zero intensity occurs at phi = pi (complete destructive interference). At phi = pi/2 the waves are partially in phase and the intensity is non-zero.", "misconception": "Confusing phi = pi/2 with destructive interference"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In Young''s double slit experiment, if the entire apparatus is immersed in a liquid of refractive index mu, the fringe width will:", "explanation": "In a medium of refractive index mu, the wavelength becomes lambda'' = lambda/mu. Since fringe width beta = lambda*D/d, the new fringe width beta'' = (lambda/mu)*D/d = beta/mu. Since mu > 1, the fringe width decreases.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["fringe-width", "refractive-index", "ydse-in-medium"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-07", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Decrease by a factor of mu", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Increase by a factor of mu", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Remain unchanged", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Decrease by a factor of mu^2", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Wavelength decreases in a denser medium, so fringe width must decrease, not increase.", "misconception": "Thinking wavelength increases in a denser medium"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Fringe width depends on wavelength, which changes in a medium. The frequency remains unchanged, but the wavelength changes.", "misconception": "Forgetting that wavelength changes in a medium"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The relationship is linear: beta is proportional to lambda, and lambda is proportional to 1/mu. There is no squaring involved.", "misconception": "Incorrectly squaring the refractive index"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The ratio of the maximum to minimum intensity in an interference pattern when two coherent sources have intensity ratio 4:1 is:", "explanation": "If I_1/I_2 = 4/1, then sqrt(I_1)/sqrt(I_2) = 2/1. Maximum intensity I_max = (sqrt(I_1) + sqrt(I_2))^2 = (2 + 1)^2 = 9. Minimum intensity I_min = (sqrt(I_1) - sqrt(I_2))^2 = (2 - 1)^2 = 1. Therefore, I_max/I_min = 9:1.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["intensity-ratio", "constructive-destructive-interference", "amplitude-superposition"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-08", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "4:1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "5:3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "25:9", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "9:1", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "4:1 is the ratio of the individual source intensities, not the maximum-to-minimum ratio. You need to use amplitude addition and subtraction.", "misconception": "Confusing source intensity ratio with fringe intensity ratio"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "5:3 would come from adding and subtracting intensities directly (4+1):(4-1), but intensities do not add this way in interference. Amplitudes add, and intensity is proportional to amplitude squared.", "misconception": "Adding intensities directly instead of amplitudes"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "25:9 would result from an incorrect formula. The correct approach uses (sqrt(I_1) + sqrt(I_2))^2 / (sqrt(I_1) - sqrt(I_2))^2.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In thin film interference, an oil film of thickness t and refractive index mu appears bright in reflected light when (for near-normal incidence):", "explanation": "In thin film interference in reflected light, there is an extra phase change of pi (equivalent to lambda/2 path difference) at the top surface where light reflects from a denser medium. The condition for constructive interference (bright film) becomes 2*mu*t = (2n - 1)*lambda/2, i.e., the optical path difference 2*mu*t equals an odd multiple of lambda/2.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["thin-film-interference", "reflected-light", "optical-path-difference"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-09", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "2*mu*t = n*lambda", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "2*mu*t = (2n - 1)*lambda/2", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "2*t = n*lambda", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "mu*t = n*lambda", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "2*mu*t = n*lambda is the condition for destructive interference (dark) in reflected light, because the additional phase change at the top surface shifts the constructive condition.", "misconception": "Forgetting the extra phase change of pi at the denser medium reflection"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This formula ignores the refractive index mu. The optical path inside the film is 2*mu*t, not 2*t.", "misconception": "Ignoring the refractive index in thin film calculations"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The light traverses the film twice (down and back up), so the path is 2*mu*t, not mu*t.", "misconception": "Forgetting the factor of 2 for double traversal"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "In Young''s double slit experiment with slit separation 1 mm and screen distance 1 m, two wavelengths lambda_1 = 600 nm and lambda_2 = 480 nm are used. The minimum distance from the central maximum where bright fringes of both wavelengths coincide is:", "explanation": "For the bright fringes to coincide, n_1*lambda_1 = n_2*lambda_2 (same path difference). So n_1*600 = n_2*480, giving n_1/n_2 = 480/600 = 4/5. The minimum integers satisfying this are n_1 = 4 and n_2 = 5. The distance from the central maximum = n_1*lambda_1*D/d = 4 * 600 x 10^-9 * 1 / (1 x 10^-3) = 2400 x 10^-6 m = 2.4 mm.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["ydse-two-wavelengths", "fringe-coincidence", "numerical-problem"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-10", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1.2 mm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1.8 mm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "2.4 mm", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "3.0 mm", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "1.2 mm corresponds to n_1 = 2 for lambda_1. Check whether n_2 is an integer: 2 x 600/480 = 2.5, which is not an integer, so fringes do not coincide here.", "misconception": "Not checking if both fringe orders are integers"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "1.8 mm corresponds to n_1 = 3 for lambda_1. Check: n_2 = 3 x 600/480 = 3.75, which is not an integer.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "3.0 mm corresponds to n_1 = 5 for lambda_1. While n_2 = 5 x 600/480 = 6.25 is not an integer, the minimum coincidence occurs at n_1 = 4, n_2 = 5.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "In Newton''s rings experiment, the radius of the n-th dark ring is proportional to:", "explanation": "In Newton''s rings, the radius of the n-th dark ring is given by r_n = sqrt(n*lambda*R), where R is the radius of curvature of the plano-convex lens and lambda is the wavelength. Therefore, r_n is proportional to sqrt(n).", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["newtons-rings", "dark-ring-radius", "thin-film-interference"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-11", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "sqrt(n)", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "n", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "n^2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "1/n", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The radius is proportional to sqrt(n), not n. The area enclosed by the ring is proportional to n, which may cause confusion.", "misconception": "Confusing ring radius with ring area proportionality"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "n^2 dependence would mean rings spread out rapidly, which contradicts the observation that Newton''s rings get closer together for higher orders.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "1/n would mean higher-order rings have smaller radii, which is physically incorrect. Higher-order rings are always farther from the centre.", "misconception": "Inverting the relationship between ring number and radius"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "When white light is used in Young''s double slit experiment, the central fringe is:", "explanation": "At the central position, the path difference is zero for all wavelengths. Therefore, all wavelengths undergo constructive interference at the central point, and the central fringe appears white. Away from the centre, different wavelengths produce maxima at different positions, leading to coloured fringes.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["white-light-interference", "central-fringe", "ydse"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-12", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Red", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Violet", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Dark", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "White", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Red fringes appear at positions where only red light undergoes constructive interference. The central fringe has zero path difference for all colours, not just red.", "misconception": "Thinking only one colour dominates at the centre"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Similar to red, violet alone does not dominate the central position. All wavelengths constructively interfere at zero path difference.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "A dark fringe would require destructive interference, which cannot occur at zero path difference where all wavelengths are in phase.", "misconception": "Thinking superposition of all colours causes cancellation"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): In Young''s double slit experiment, the fringe pattern shifts when a thin transparent glass plate is introduced in the path of one of the beams. Reason (R): The glass plate introduces an additional optical path difference because light travels slower in glass than in air.", "explanation": "Assertion is correct: introducing a glass plate of thickness t and refractive index mu in one beam introduces an extra optical path of (mu - 1)*t, shifting the central fringe to a new position. Reason is also correct: light travels slower in glass (speed = c/mu), so the optical path length increases. The Reason correctly explains the Assertion because it is precisely because of the increased optical path (due to slower speed in glass) that the fringe pattern shifts.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["glass-plate-in-ydse", "optical-path-difference", "fringe-shift"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-13", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The reason directly explains the assertion. The fringe shift occurs precisely because the glass introduces an additional optical path due to the reduced speed of light in glass.", "misconception": "Failing to see the causal link between slower light speed and fringe shift"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is factually correct. Light does travel slower in glass (v = c/mu, and mu > 1 for glass), increasing the optical path.", "misconception": "Thinking the speed of light does not change in glass"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct. Inserting a glass plate in one beam path is a well-known method to shift the fringe pattern in YDSE.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): Two independent laser sources of the same frequency cannot produce a sustained interference pattern. Reason (R): For sustained interference, the two sources must be derived from the same parent source to maintain a constant phase relationship.", "explanation": "Assertion is correct: even two lasers of nominally the same frequency have independent, randomly fluctuating phases. Over time, the phase difference varies, and the interference pattern averages out, so no sustained pattern is observed. Reason is also correct and is the correct explanation: deriving both beams from a single source (as in YDSE) ensures a constant phase difference, which is essential for a stable interference pattern.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["coherent-sources", "independent-sources", "sustained-interference", "laser-coherence"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-14", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The reason directly addresses why independent sources fail: the lack of a common parent source means no constant phase relationship. This is exactly why the assertion is true.", "misconception": "Not seeing the direct causal connection between same parent source and sustained interference"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is correct. Deriving two beams from a single source (e.g., by splitting) does maintain coherence, which is a fundamental principle of wave optics.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct. Even high-quality lasers have independent phase fluctuations, making sustained interference impossible without deriving beams from the same source.", "misconception": "Thinking that same-frequency lasers are automatically coherent with each other"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match Column I with Column II:\n\nColumn I:\nA. Path difference = n*lambda\nB. Path difference = (2n - 1)*lambda/2\nC. Phase difference = 0\nD. Phase difference = pi\n\nColumn II:\n1. Destructive interference\n2. Constructive interference\n3. Maximum intensity\n4. Minimum (zero) intensity", "explanation": "A. Path difference = n*lambda corresponds to constructive interference (2). B. Path difference = (2n-1)*lambda/2 corresponds to destructive interference (1). C. Phase difference = 0 means the waves are perfectly in phase, giving maximum intensity (3). D. Phase difference = pi means the waves are completely out of phase, giving minimum/zero intensity (4). So the correct matching is A-2, B-1, C-3, D-4.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["path-difference", "phase-difference", "constructive-destructive-interference"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-15", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-1, B-2, C-4, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-2, B-1, C-4, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-3, B-4, C-2, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-2, B-1, C-3, D-4", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This reverses constructive and destructive interference conditions. Path difference n*lambda gives constructive (not destructive) interference.", "misconception": "Confusing conditions for constructive and destructive interference"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "C-4 and D-3 are reversed. Phase difference 0 means waves are in phase (maximum intensity), while phase difference pi means they cancel (minimum intensity).", "misconception": "Confusing zero phase difference with minimum intensity"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Path difference n*lambda leads to constructive interference, not directly maximum intensity as a separate concept. Check each match individually.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match Column I with Column II:\n\nColumn I:\nA. Fringe width (beta) when wavelength is doubled\nB. Fringe width when slit separation is halved\nC. Fringe width when screen distance is tripled\nD. Fringe width when experiment is done in water (mu = 4/3)\n\nColumn II:\n1. beta becomes 3*beta\n2. beta becomes 2*beta\n3. beta becomes (3/4)*beta\n4. beta becomes 2*beta", "explanation": "Using beta = lambda*D/d: A. lambda doubled: beta'' = 2*lambda*D/d = 2*beta (matches 2). B. d halved: beta'' = lambda*D/(d/2) = 2*beta (matches 4). C. D tripled: beta'' = lambda*3D/d = 3*beta (matches 1). D. In water (mu = 4/3): lambda'' = lambda/mu = 3*lambda/4, so beta'' = (3/4)*beta (matches 3). Correct matching: A-2, B-4, C-1, D-3.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["fringe-width-variations", "ydse-parameters", "refractive-index-effect"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-16", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-1, B-2, C-3, D-4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-2, B-3, C-1, D-4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-2, B-4, C-1, D-3", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-4, B-2, C-3, D-1", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Doubling lambda gives 2*beta, not 3*beta. Check the proportionality: beta is directly proportional to lambda.", "misconception": "Incorrect proportionality assessment"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Halving d gives 2*beta (matches 4), not (3/4)*beta (which is 3). Check: beta is inversely proportional to d.", "misconception": "Confusing inverse and direct proportionality with slit separation"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This option assigns completely incorrect factors. Systematically apply beta = lambda*D/d with each change separately.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In Young''s double slit experiment, the fringe width is directly proportional to the wavelength of light used.", "explanation": "This statement is TRUE. From the fringe width formula beta = lambda*D/d, we can see that beta is directly proportional to lambda (keeping D and d constant). If the wavelength increases, the fringe width increases proportionally, and if the wavelength decreases, the fringe width decreases proportionally.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["fringe-width", "wavelength-dependence", "ydse-formula"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-17", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The formula beta = lambda*D/d clearly shows lambda in the numerator with a power of 1, confirming a directly proportional relationship.", "misconception": "Thinking fringe width is inversely proportional to wavelength"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This is not a valid option for this question.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is not a valid option for this question.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In the interference pattern produced by two coherent sources, energy is destroyed at the positions of dark fringes.", "explanation": "This statement is FALSE. Energy is NOT destroyed at dark fringes. The principle of conservation of energy holds. In interference, energy is redistributed: the energy missing from dark fringes (minima) appears at the bright fringes (maxima). The total energy remains constant; it is merely redistributed in space.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["energy-conservation", "interference-pattern", "energy-redistribution"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-18", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Energy can neither be created nor destroyed. In interference, energy from dark fringes is redistributed to bright fringes, conserving total energy.", "misconception": "Thinking that zero intensity at minima means energy is lost"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This is not a valid option for this question.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is not a valid option for this question.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In Young''s double slit experiment, if the two slits are illuminated by monochromatic light of wavelength 600 nm with slit separation 0.3 mm and screen distance 1.5 m, the distance between the 4th bright fringe and the 4th dark fringe on the same side of the central maximum is _____.", "explanation": "Fringe width beta = lambda*D/d = (600 x 10^-9 x 1.5) / (0.3 x 10^-3) = 9 x 10^-7 / 3 x 10^-4 = 3 x 10^-3 m = 3 mm. Position of the 4th bright fringe = 4*beta = 12 mm. Position of the 4th dark fringe = (4 - 1/2)*beta = 3.5*beta = 10.5 mm. The distance between them = 12 - 10.5 = 1.5 mm = beta/2.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["fringe-position", "bright-dark-fringe-distance", "numerical-problem"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-19", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "3 mm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1.5 mm", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "0.75 mm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "6 mm", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "3 mm is the fringe width itself. The distance between adjacent bright and dark fringes (of the same order, same side) is beta/2, not beta.", "misconception": "Confusing fringe width with the bright-dark fringe separation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "0.75 mm = beta/4, which has no standard significance in YDSE fringe separation. The separation between the n-th bright and n-th dark fringe on the same side is always beta/2.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "6 mm = 2*beta. This does not correspond to any standard fringe separation. Recalculate the positions of the 4th bright and 4th dark fringes.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-interference", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "A student performs Young''s double slit experiment in the laboratory. The slit separation is 0.2 mm and the screen is 1 m away. Using a sodium lamp (lambda = 589 nm), the student observes a clear fringe pattern. The student then covers one of the slits. Which of the following correctly describes what happens to the pattern on the screen?", "explanation": "When one slit is blocked, there is no longer two-source interference. Instead, light passes through only a single slit, producing a single-slit diffraction pattern. This pattern has a broad central maximum with much wider and less distinct secondary maxima, and the sharp equidistant interference fringes disappear. The central diffraction maximum is much broader than the interference fringes, and the intensity distribution changes from the cos^2 modulation of YDSE to the sinc^2 pattern of single-slit diffraction.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["ydse-single-slit", "diffraction-vs-interference", "experimental-observation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-interference-20", "subtopic": "Interference of Light", "topic_name": "Interference of Light", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The fringe width doubles because only one slit contributes", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "The screen becomes completely dark", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "The interference fringes disappear and a broad single-slit diffraction pattern is observed", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "The fringes become brighter but otherwise remain unchanged", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The fringe width formula beta = lambda*D/d applies only to double-slit interference. With one slit covered, there is no two-source interference and hence no interference fringes to have a ''width''.", "misconception": "Thinking double-slit interference pattern persists with one slit blocked"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Light still passes through the open slit and illuminates the screen. One slit produces a diffraction pattern, not darkness.", "misconception": "Thinking interference is needed for any light to reach the screen"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The pattern fundamentally changes from equidistant interference fringes to a broad diffraction envelope. The two patterns are qualitatively different.", "misconception": "Not distinguishing between interference and diffraction patterns"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The phenomenon of polarisation of light proves that light is:", "explanation": "Polarisation is the phenomenon in which the vibrations of the electric field vector of a light wave are confined to a single plane. Only transverse waves can be polarised because longitudinal waves oscillate along the direction of propagation and cannot be restricted to a single plane. Since light can be polarised, it proves that light is a transverse wave.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["polarisation", "transverse-wave", "nature-of-light"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-01", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A transverse wave", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "A longitudinal wave", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Both transverse and longitudinal", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Neither transverse nor longitudinal", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Longitudinal waves (like sound in air) oscillate along the direction of propagation. Such waves cannot exhibit polarisation because there is no perpendicular component to restrict.", "misconception": "Confusing longitudinal and transverse wave properties"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "If light were longitudinal, it could not be polarised. Polarisation is exclusively a property of transverse waves.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Light is a well-characterised electromagnetic wave. Polarisation specifically identifies it as transverse.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "When unpolarised light of intensity I₀ passes through a single Polaroid, the intensity of the transmitted light is:", "explanation": "Unpolarised light has electric field vibrations in all directions perpendicular to propagation. A Polaroid transmits only the component of vibration along its pass axis. On averaging cos²θ over all angles (0 to 2π), the average value of cos²θ is 1/2. Therefore, the transmitted intensity is I₀/2.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["polaroid", "unpolarised-light", "intensity-reduction"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-02", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "I₀", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "I₀/2", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "I₀/4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Zero", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "If the full intensity were transmitted, the Polaroid would have no effect at all. A Polaroid always absorbs the component of light perpendicular to its pass axis.", "misconception": "Assuming Polaroid transmits all light"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "I₀/4 would be the result after passing through two crossed Polaroids with an intermediate Polaroid at 45°. A single Polaroid transmits I₀/2.", "misconception": "Confusing single Polaroid with two-Polaroid system"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Zero intensity would occur only if the light were already polarised perpendicular to the Polaroid''s pass axis. Unpolarised light always has some component along the pass axis.", "misconception": "Confusing unpolarised light with cross-polarised light"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "According to Brewster''s law, the polarising angle iₚ for a medium of refractive index μ is given by:", "explanation": "Brewster''s law states that when light is incident on a transparent surface at the polarising angle iₚ, the reflected light is completely plane polarised. The relationship is tan iₚ = μ, where μ is the refractive index of the medium. At this angle, the reflected and refracted rays are perpendicular to each other.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["brewster-law", "polarising-angle", "refractive-index"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-03", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "sin iₚ = μ", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "cos iₚ = μ", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "tan iₚ = μ", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "cot iₚ = μ", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "sin iₚ = μ is Snell''s law form and would require μ ≤ 1 for any real angle, which is not generally true for denser media.", "misconception": "Confusing Brewster''s law with Snell''s law"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "cos iₚ = μ would also require μ ≤ 1 and has no physical basis in the derivation of Brewster''s condition.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "cot iₚ = μ is the inverse of the correct relation. Brewster''s law uses tangent, not cotangent.", "misconception": "Inverting the Brewster''s law relation"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "Polaroid sunglasses reduce glare from surfaces because they:", "explanation": "Light reflected from horizontal surfaces such as roads and water is partially polarised with the electric field vibrating predominantly in the horizontal plane. Polaroid sunglasses have their pass axis oriented vertically, which blocks this horizontally polarised glare while transmitting the vertically polarised component of light from other sources, thereby reducing glare without making everything dark.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["polaroid", "applications-of-polarisation", "glare-reduction"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-04", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Absorb all light equally, reducing overall brightness", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Reflect all incoming light back towards the source", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Diffract the light around the edges of the lens", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Block the horizontally polarised component of reflected light", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "If they absorbed all light equally, they would just be tinted lenses. Polaroid lenses specifically reduce glare by selectively blocking polarised light.", "misconception": "Confusing Polaroid with ordinary tinted glass"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Polaroid lenses do not reflect light; they absorb one polarisation component while transmitting the other.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Diffraction is the bending of light around obstacles and is unrelated to glare reduction by Polaroid lenses.", "misconception": null}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b14');

SELECT insert_batch_questions('[{"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Plane polarised light of intensity I₀ passes through a Polaroid whose pass axis makes an angle of 60° with the plane of polarisation. The intensity of the transmitted light is:", "explanation": "According to Malus''s law, when plane polarised light of intensity I₀ passes through a Polaroid (analyser), the transmitted intensity is I = I₀cos²θ, where θ is the angle between the polarisation direction and the pass axis of the analyser. Here θ = 60°, so I = I₀cos²60° = I₀ × (1/2)² = I₀/4.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["malus-law", "plane-polarised-light", "intensity"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-05", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "I₀/2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "I₀/4", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "3I₀/4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "I₀/8", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "I₀/2 would be the result for θ = 45° (since cos²45° = 1/2), not for θ = 60°.", "misconception": "Using wrong angle value or confusing with single Polaroid on unpolarised light"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "3I₀/4 = I₀ × cos²30°, which would apply if θ = 30°, not 60°. Check the angle carefully.", "misconception": "Using the complementary angle instead of the given angle"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "I₀/8 does not correspond to cos²θ for any standard angle. For θ = 60°, cos²60° = (1/2)² = 1/4.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The Brewster''s angle for a glass surface of refractive index 1.5 is approximately:", "explanation": "Using Brewster''s law: tan iₚ = μ = 1.5. Therefore iₚ = tan⁻¹(1.5). Computing: tan⁻¹(1.5) ≈ 56.3°. At this angle, the reflected light is completely plane polarised and the reflected and refracted rays are perpendicular to each other.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["brewster-angle", "refractive-index", "polarisation-by-reflection"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-06", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "33.7°", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "45°", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "56.3°", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "60°", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "33.7° is the complement of the Brewster angle (90° - 56.3°). This is actually the angle of refraction at Brewster''s angle, not the Brewster angle itself.", "misconception": "Confusing the angle of refraction with the polarising angle"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "45° would be the Brewster angle only if μ = tan 45° = 1, which would mean both media have the same refractive index.", "misconception": "Assuming Brewster''s angle is always 45°"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "tan 60° = √3 ≈ 1.732, which corresponds to μ = √3, not μ = 1.5.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "At Brewster''s angle, the angle between the reflected ray and the refracted ray is:", "explanation": "At Brewster''s angle, the reflected ray and the refracted ray are perpendicular to each other, i.e., the angle between them is 90°. This is because at the polarising angle iₚ, we have iₚ + r = 90° (where r is the angle of refraction). Since the reflected ray makes angle iₚ with the normal and the refracted ray makes angle r with the normal, the angle between the reflected and refracted rays is iₚ + r = 90°. Wait -- more precisely, the reflected ray is on the same side as the incident ray making angle iₚ with the normal, while the refracted ray is on the other side making angle r with the normal. The angle between them measured from the surface is (90° - iₚ) + (90° - r) = 180° - (iₚ + r) = 180° - 90° = 90°.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["brewster-angle", "reflected-refracted-perpendicular", "polarisation-by-reflection"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-07", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "90°", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "60°", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "180°", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "It depends on the refractive index of the medium", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "60° would be the angle only for a specific refractive index, but the perpendicularity of reflected and refracted rays at Brewster''s angle holds for all media.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "180° would mean the reflected and refracted rays are in the same direction, which is physically impossible since they are on opposite sides of the interface.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "While the Brewster angle itself depends on μ, the angle between reflected and refracted rays at Brewster''s angle is always 90°, regardless of the medium.", "misconception": "Thinking the 90° relationship varies with material"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Two Polaroids P₁ and P₂ are placed with their pass axes perpendicular to each other. Unpolarised light of intensity I₀ is incident on P₁. A third Polaroid P₃ is placed between P₁ and P₂ with its pass axis at 45° to that of P₁. The intensity of light emerging from P₂ is:", "explanation": "After P₁: intensity = I₀/2 (unpolarised light through a Polaroid). After P₃ (at 45° to P₁): I = (I₀/2)cos²45° = (I₀/2)(1/2) = I₀/4. After P₂ (at 45° to P₃, since P₂ is perpendicular to P₁ and P₃ is at 45° to P₁): I = (I₀/4)cos²45° = (I₀/4)(1/2) = I₀/8.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["malus-law", "crossed-polaroids", "intermediate-polaroid"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-08", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "I₀/2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "I₀/4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Zero", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "I₀/8", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "I₀/2 is only the intensity after the first Polaroid. You must apply Malus''s law at each subsequent Polaroid.", "misconception": "Forgetting to apply Malus''s law at intermediate and final stages"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "I₀/4 is the intensity after passing through P₃ but before passing through P₂. One more application of Malus''s law is needed.", "misconception": "Stopping the calculation after the intermediate Polaroid"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Zero would be the result if only P₁ and P₂ (crossed) were present. The intermediate Polaroid P₃ at 45° allows some light to pass through.", "misconception": "Ignoring the effect of the intermediate Polaroid between crossed Polaroids"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Unpolarised light is incident on a Polaroid. The Polaroid is then rotated about the direction of the incident light. The intensity of the transmitted light:", "explanation": "When unpolarised light passes through a Polaroid, the transmitted intensity is always I₀/2, regardless of the orientation of the Polaroid''s pass axis. This is because unpolarised light has vibrations uniformly distributed in all directions perpendicular to propagation. Rotating the Polaroid simply changes which component is transmitted, but the average intensity remains the same at I₀/2.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["polaroid", "unpolarised-light", "rotation-of-polaroid"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-09", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Remains constant at I₀/2", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Varies between 0 and I₀", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Varies between 0 and I₀/2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Becomes zero at certain orientations", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Variation between 0 and I₀ occurs only when plane polarised light passes through a rotating analyser (Malus''s law). For unpolarised incident light, the Polaroid output is constant.", "misconception": "Confusing unpolarised light behaviour with polarised light behaviour through a rotating analyser"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "There is no variation at all. Unpolarised light has no preferred direction of vibration, so all orientations of the Polaroid give the same result.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Zero intensity occurs only when plane polarised light is incident on a Polaroid with its pass axis perpendicular to the polarisation direction. Unpolarised light always gives non-zero transmission.", "misconception": "Confusing crossed Polaroid effect with single Polaroid on unpolarised light"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The sky appears blue due to scattering of sunlight by air molecules. The scattered light observed at 90° to the direction of sunlight is:", "explanation": "When sunlight is scattered by small air molecules (Rayleigh scattering), the scattered light is partially polarised. At exactly 90° to the direction of incident sunlight, the scattered light is completely plane polarised. This is because the oscillating electric dipoles induced in air molecules cannot radiate energy along their axis of oscillation, so light scattered at 90° has only one vibration direction.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["polarisation-by-scattering", "rayleigh-scattering", "plane-polarised-light"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-10", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Unpolarised", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Completely plane polarised", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "Circularly polarised", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Elliptically polarised", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The scattered light is not unpolarised. Scattering by molecules introduces polarisation, and at 90° it is fully polarised.", "misconception": "Assuming scattered light retains the same polarisation state as incident light"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Circularly polarised light has two perpendicular components with a 90° phase difference. Scattering does not introduce such a phase relationship.", "misconception": "Confusing different types of polarisation"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Elliptical polarisation also requires a specific phase relationship between perpendicular components. Scattering at 90° produces linearly (plane) polarised light.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Unpolarised light of intensity I₀ passes through three Polaroids. The first Polaroid has its pass axis vertical. The second has its pass axis at 30° to the vertical, and the third has its pass axis at 60° to the vertical. The intensity of light emerging from the third Polaroid is:", "explanation": "After Polaroid 1: I₁ = I₀/2 (unpolarised to polarised). After Polaroid 2 (angle between pass axes = 30°): I₂ = (I₀/2)cos²30° = (I₀/2)(3/4) = 3I₀/8. After Polaroid 3 (angle between pass axis of Polaroid 2 and Polaroid 3 = 60° - 30° = 30°): I₃ = (3I₀/8)cos²30° = (3I₀/8)(3/4) = 9I₀/32.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["malus-law", "multiple-polaroids", "intensity-calculation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-11", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "I₀/8", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "3I₀/8", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "9I₀/32", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "3I₀/32", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "I₀/8 would result from using 60° as the angle at both Polaroid 2 and Polaroid 3. The angle in Malus''s law is between consecutive pass axes, not from the first.", "misconception": "Using the angle relative to the first Polaroid rather than the previous one"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "3I₀/8 is the intensity after the second Polaroid. You still need to apply Malus''s law for the third Polaroid.", "misconception": "Stopping the calculation prematurely"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "3I₀/32 results from incorrectly using cos²60° at the second stage and cos²30° at the third stage, or some other error in angles.", "misconception": "Incorrectly assigning angles between consecutive Polaroids"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Light reflected from a water surface (μ = 4/3) is completely polarised. The angle of refraction of the transmitted light is:", "explanation": "For complete polarisation of reflected light, the angle of incidence equals Brewster''s angle iₚ, where tan iₚ = μ = 4/3. At Brewster''s angle, iₚ + r = 90°, so r = 90° - iₚ. Since tan iₚ = 4/3, we get iₚ = tan⁻¹(4/3) ≈ 53.1°. Therefore r = 90° - 53.1° = 36.9° ≈ 37°. Alternatively, since tan iₚ = μ and iₚ + r = 90°, then tan r = 1/μ = 3/4, giving r = tan⁻¹(3/4) ≈ 36.9°.", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["brewster-angle", "angle-of-refraction", "complete-polarisation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-12", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "53°", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "45°", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "30°", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "37°", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "53° is the Brewster''s angle (angle of incidence), not the angle of refraction. At Brewster''s angle, r = 90° - iₚ.", "misconception": "Confusing the angle of incidence with the angle of refraction at Brewster''s angle"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "45° would be the refraction angle if the Brewster angle were also 45°, which requires μ = 1. For μ = 4/3, this is not the case.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "30° does not satisfy the relation r = 90° - iₚ for μ = 4/3. The correct refraction angle is 90° - 53° = 37°.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): Sound waves in air cannot be polarised.\nReason (R): Polarisation is a phenomenon exclusive to transverse waves, and sound waves in air are longitudinal in nature.", "explanation": "Both the assertion and the reason are correct. Sound waves in air are longitudinal waves where particles oscillate along the direction of propagation. Polarisation requires vibrations perpendicular to the direction of propagation, which is possible only in transverse waves. Since sound in air is longitudinal, it cannot be polarised. The reason correctly explains why the assertion is true.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["polarisation", "transverse-wave", "longitudinal-wave", "sound-waves"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-13", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The reason directly explains the assertion: sound in air is longitudinal, and only transverse waves can be polarised, so sound cannot be polarised.", "misconception": "Failing to recognise the direct causal link between the nature of sound waves and impossibility of polarisation"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The reason is factually correct. Sound in air is indeed longitudinal, and polarisation is indeed exclusive to transverse waves.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct. Sound waves in air are longitudinal and cannot be polarised. This is experimentally verified.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion-reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): When unpolarised light is reflected at Brewster''s angle from a glass surface, the reflected and refracted rays are perpendicular to each other.\nReason (R): At Brewster''s angle, the refracted light is completely plane polarised.", "explanation": "The assertion is correct. At Brewster''s angle, iₚ + r = 90°, meaning the reflected and refracted rays are indeed perpendicular. The reason, however, is incorrect. At Brewster''s angle, it is the reflected light (not the refracted light) that is completely plane polarised. The refracted light is only partially polarised. Therefore, A is correct but R is incorrect.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["brewster-angle", "reflected-refracted-perpendicular", "polarisation-by-reflection"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-14", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Check the reason carefully. At Brewster''s angle, it is the reflected light that is completely polarised, not the refracted light.", "misconception": "Confusing which ray (reflected vs refracted) is completely polarised at Brewster''s angle"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The reason itself contains a factual error. The refracted light at Brewster''s angle is only partially polarised, not completely polarised.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The assertion is correct. The perpendicularity of reflected and refracted rays at Brewster''s angle (iₚ + r = 90°) is a well-established fact.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match the phenomena in Column I with their descriptions in Column II:\n\nColumn I:\nA. Malus''s law\nB. Brewster''s law\nC. Double refraction\nD. Optical activity\n\nColumn II:\n1. tan iₚ = μ\n2. I = I₀cos²θ\n3. Rotation of the plane of polarisation by certain substances\n4. Splitting of a light ray into ordinary and extraordinary rays in a crystal", "explanation": "Malus''s law gives the intensity of polarised light after passing through an analyser as I = I₀cos²θ (A-2). Brewster''s law relates the polarising angle to the refractive index as tan iₚ = μ (B-1). Double refraction is the phenomenon where a crystal splits an incident ray into ordinary and extraordinary rays (C-4). Optical activity is the property of certain substances to rotate the plane of polarisation of light passing through them (D-3).", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["malus-law", "brewster-law", "double-refraction", "optical-activity"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-15", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-1, B-2, C-4, D-3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-2, B-1, C-4, D-3", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-2, B-1, C-3, D-4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-1, B-2, C-3, D-4", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This swaps A and B. Malus''s law is I = I₀cos²θ (A-2), and Brewster''s law is tan iₚ = μ (B-1), not the reverse.", "misconception": "Interchanging Malus''s law and Brewster''s law formulas"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This swaps C and D. Double refraction involves splitting into O and E rays (C-4), and optical activity involves rotation of the polarisation plane (D-3).", "misconception": "Confusing double refraction with optical activity"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This has all four matchings incorrect. Both A-B and C-D pairs are swapped compared to the correct matching.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match-the-following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match the polarisation methods in Column I with their key features in Column II:\n\nColumn I:\nA. Polarisation by reflection\nB. Polarisation by scattering\nC. Polarisation by selective absorption (Polaroid)\nD. Polarisation by double refraction\n\nColumn II:\n1. Uses dichroic crystals or stretched polymer sheets containing aligned molecules\n2. Produces two refracted rays with mutually perpendicular polarisations inside a birefringent crystal\n3. Completely polarises reflected light when incidence is at Brewster''s angle\n4. Light scattered at 90° to the incident beam is completely plane polarised", "explanation": "Polarisation by reflection completely polarises the reflected light at Brewster''s angle (A-3). Polarisation by scattering produces completely polarised light at 90° to the incident direction (B-4). Polaroids use dichroic materials or aligned polymer molecules for selective absorption (C-1). Double refraction in birefringent crystals produces ordinary and extraordinary rays with mutually perpendicular polarisations (D-2).", "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["polarisation-by-reflection", "polarisation-by-scattering", "polaroid", "double-refraction"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-16", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A-3, B-1, C-4, D-2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "A-4, B-3, C-1, D-2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A-3, B-4, C-2, D-1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A-3, B-4, C-1, D-2", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This swaps B and C. Scattering polarises light at 90° (B-4), not Polaroids. Polaroids use selective absorption (C-1), not scattering.", "misconception": "Confusing polarisation by scattering with selective absorption"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "This swaps A and B. Polarisation by reflection occurs at Brewster''s angle (A-3), while scattering polarises at 90° (B-4).", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This swaps C and D. Polaroids use dichroic/aligned molecules (C-1), and double refraction produces O and E rays in birefringent crystals (D-2).", "misconception": "Interchanging Polaroid mechanism with double refraction"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "According to Malus''s law, when polarised light passes through an analyser with its pass axis parallel to the polarisation direction (θ = 0°), the transmitted intensity equals the incident intensity.", "explanation": "This statement is true. According to Malus''s law, I = I₀cos²θ. When θ = 0° (pass axis parallel to polarisation direction), cos 0° = 1, so I = I₀cos²0° = I₀ × 1 = I₀. The full intensity of the polarised light is transmitted.", "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["malus-law", "parallel-polarisation", "intensity"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-17", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Substituting θ = 0° into Malus''s law gives I = I₀ × cos²0° = I₀ × 1 = I₀, confirming the statement is true.", "misconception": "Incorrectly recalling Malus''s law formula"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true-false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "At Brewster''s angle, both the reflected and refracted light are completely plane polarised.", "explanation": "This statement is false. At Brewster''s angle, only the reflected light is completely plane polarised (with vibrations perpendicular to the plane of incidence). The refracted (transmitted) light is only partially polarised because it still contains both components of vibration, though the component in the plane of incidence is enhanced relative to the perpendicular component.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["brewster-angle", "reflected-light-polarisation", "refracted-light-partial-polarisation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-18", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Only the reflected light is completely polarised at Brewster''s angle. The refracted light is partially polarised, not completely polarised.", "misconception": "Assuming both reflected and refracted rays are fully polarised at Brewster''s angle"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is a placeholder option and not a valid choice.", "misconception": null}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill-in-blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In a calcite crystal, the phenomenon of double refraction produces two rays: the _____ ray which obeys Snell''s law and the extraordinary ray which does not obey Snell''s law.", "explanation": "When light enters a birefringent (doubly refracting) crystal like calcite, it splits into two rays. The ordinary ray (O-ray) obeys Snell''s law of refraction and travels with the same speed in all directions within the crystal. The extraordinary ray (E-ray) does not obey Snell''s law and its speed varies with direction inside the crystal. Both rays are plane polarised with their vibration directions perpendicular to each other.", "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["double-refraction", "ordinary-ray", "extraordinary-ray", "calcite"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-19", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "refracted", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "ordinary", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "polarised", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "diffracted", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "Both rays are refracted rays. The specific terminology used in double refraction is ''ordinary'' for the ray obeying Snell''s law and ''extraordinary'' for the one that does not.", "misconception": "Using a generic term instead of the specific terminology of double refraction"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Both the ordinary and extraordinary rays are polarised. The blank specifically refers to the ray that obeys Snell''s law, which is called the ordinary ray.", "misconception": null}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "Diffraction is bending of light around obstacles and is unrelated to double refraction in crystals.", "misconception": "Confusing refraction in crystals with diffraction"}]}}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-optics", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-opt-polarisation", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario-based", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "An engineer is testing the structural integrity of a transparent plastic bridge model using photoelasticity (stress analysis). She places the model between two crossed Polaroids and observes coloured fringe patterns at stress concentration points when white light is used.\n\nUnpolarised light of intensity I₀ is first passed through a polariser. It then passes through the stressed plastic model, which rotates the plane of polarisation by 30°. Finally, the light passes through an analyser whose pass axis is perpendicular to the polariser''s pass axis. What is the intensity of light emerging from the analyser?", "explanation": "After the polariser: I₁ = I₀/2 (unpolarised to polarised). The stressed plastic rotates the polarisation direction by 30°. Since the analyser is perpendicular to the polariser (90° apart), and the polarisation has been rotated by 30°, the angle between the polarisation direction of light entering the analyser and the analyser''s pass axis is 90° - 30° = 60°. Applying Malus''s law: I₂ = I₁cos²60° = (I₀/2)(1/2)² = (I₀/2)(1/4) = I₀/8.", "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["malus-law", "stress-analysis", "photoelasticity", "crossed-polaroids", "rotation-of-polarisation"], "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-waveopt-polarisation-20", "subtopic": "Polarisation of Light", "topic_name": "Polarisation of Light", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "I₀/4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "3I₀/8", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "I₀/8", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "I₀/2", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "I₀/4 would result if the angle with the analyser were 45° (cos²45° = 1/2 applied to I₀/2). But the rotation is 30°, making the effective angle 60° with the analyser.", "misconception": "Using the rotation angle directly instead of computing the angle relative to the analyser"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "3I₀/8 = (I₀/2)cos²30°. This would be correct if the angle between the rotated polarisation and the analyser were 30°, but it is actually 90° - 30° = 60°.", "misconception": "Using the rotation angle (30°) instead of the angle with the analyser''s pass axis (60°)"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "I₀/2 is the intensity just after the first polariser. After the analyser, Malus''s law must be applied with the appropriate angle.", "misconception": "Forgetting to apply Malus''s law at the analyser stage"}]}}]'::jsonb, 'deploy-2026-03-05-b14');

COMMIT;
